LIFESTYLE WRITER NHIMBE Trust on December 10 hosted the Seven Keys Workshop on International Human Rights Day in Bulawayo, in partnership with the Bulawayo City Council and the United Cities and Local Governments (UCLG) Committee on Culture. The workshop, with 18 participants, was facilitated by Zayd Minty (South Africa), an expert for UCLG Agenda 21 for Culture, director of Creative City South, and a research associate for Wits University’s Cultural Policy and Management Department. Minty met the mayor and deputy mayor of Bulawayo and enjoyed a personal tour of key spaces including Khami Ruins, Bulawayo Natural History Museum, Bulawayo Art Gallery, Bulawayo/Mzilikazi Home Industries, Mzilikazi Art and Craft Centre, the home of writer and historian Pathisa Nyathi in Luveve, Bulawayo Centenary Park and the Silwane Nature Reserve. Participants at the workshop were from city council departments, civil society, government agencies and emerging city entrepreneurs. The core team comprised Kudakwashe Takundwa of Urban Culture, who is Bulawayo Cultural Affairs Office social media manager, photographer Mgcini Nyoni. The event was coordinated by Lisa Sidambe for Nhimbe Trust. The UCLG Committee on Culture is the global platform of cities, organisations and networks to learn, cooperate and to launch policies and programmes on the role of culture in sustainable development. Since its creation in May 2004, more than 240 000 towns, cities, regions and metropolises, and more than 175 local and regional government associations have joined the global network. In the context of the Seven Keys programme, a new initiative designed by UCLG Culture Committee, the workshop’s objective was to integrate the cultural dimension in localisation of Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). The workshop related municipal challenges with cultural assets, activities, and policies of Bulawayo through the lenses of the document “Culture in the Sustainable Development Goals: A Guide for Local Action” (UCLG, 2018) and the database of good practices. Workshop discussions worked towards identifying seven “keys” that Bulawayo actors can commit to localise the SDGs through culture policymaking.        Topics included Local Challenges and the SDGs Brief; Culture Mapping of the main elements considered as culture in the municipality, and current cultural policies or programmes that are or can potentially contribute to the localisation of the SDGs;  and Spotting the Gaps –  identifying other critical aspects of the SDGs. Minty said:  “As the workshop facilitator, I found great enthusiasm and positivity in our group of 18 participants, as well as the Nhimbe team. There was rich dialogue and creative engagement with eight projects emerging. “Participants wanted to have longer time to develop their ideas and this suggested a follow up may be needed. “The city council officials also needed to have clearer mandates related to how they can connect the concepts to actual council programmes, plans and budgets.  This was an excellent start to begin to think about culture’s importance in sustainable-city-making, drawing on Bulawayo’s rich, complex tangible and intangible cultural heritage. “It’s the beginning of a process rather than an end. I had been shown around Bulawayo by Nhimbe in the days before the workshop and read a great deal about the city. “I was impressed by its resonant histories, important places and the wide variety of dynamic activities going on.  It will be interesting to see how these can be connected to the city’s challenges of water, infrastructure, economy, health and well-being.” Workshop participant Reach A Young Soul (RAYS) founder Trust Dorothy Madamba said: “Thank you for including the youth, through RAYS Trust, in the workshop.  Workshops like this should be a regular occurrence to include a wider stakeholders’ pool. “Bulawayo prides itself of a rich heritage and inclusivity and seeing all the assets channelled towards development would be an all-hands-on-deck effort. With regular updates and contributions going forward we can all make a difference in our city. “After the workshop Agenda 21 for Culture posted: “Today we held our first-ever #7keys workshop in the City of Bulawayo, Zimbabwe … we are delighted to say that the workshop was a great success and we warmly thank the Nhimbe Trust and Bulawayo Cultural Affairs Office for their collaboration in the organisation of the event, as well as Zayd Minty from Creative City South for the facilitation of the meeting.”   Sponsored Links                                              Classifieds.co.zw                                                                                                                      Property, Houses                                                                                                                                                      Building Supplies                                                                                                                                                      Electronics                                                                                                                                                      Cars                                                                                                                                                      Home & Garden                                                                                                                                                      Commercial Supplies                                                                                                                                                      Services                                                                                                                                                      Health & Beauty                                                                                                                                